5. MATHEMATICAL DEFINITIONS OF ZERO-TYPES

5.1 Additive Zero Transformation

T_{+}(S) = S - \mu

Where \mu is the cognitive mean or bias.

Purpose: remove drift.

‚∏ª

5.2 Multiplicative Zero Transformation

T_{\times}(S) = \frac{S}{\|S\|}

Purpose: normalize magnitude, highlight direction.

‚∏ª

5.3 Complex Zero (Orthogonal Zero)

T_{i}(S) = S \cdot i

Interpreting ‚Äúi‚Äù as a 90¬∞ rotation in conceptual space.

Purpose: reframe the situation.

‚∏ª

5.4 Quaternion Zero (Perspective Quaternion)

T_{q}(S) = q S q^{-1}

Where q is a unit quaternion.

Purpose: rotate worldview without altering structure.

‚∏ª

5.5 Topological Zero

T_{\text{top}} : S \rightarrow S'

Where:
S \simeq S' \quad \text{under homotopy}

Purpose: allow deformation without identity loss.

This is how the Pantheon maintains identity during radical shifts (‚Äúas above, so below‚Äù).

‚∏ª

5.6 Information Zero

D_{KL}(P \parallel Q) = 0

Meaning P = Q.

Purpose: match distributions, align interpretations.

